title: For Sale:  Yugo M48 Mauser 8mm
postcontent:
******Does not include bayonet or sling!!!************

M48: 1950-1952- The initial version of the M48, with full crest, M48 mark on receiver and all machined steel parts. These rifles have not been available for a long time. They are a must for the military rifle collector. Very few of these true M48 rifles are available.

GRADE:This rifle is in very good condition. The bore looks great with deep rifling.

The M48 Mauser is a post World War II Yugoslavian version of the Belgian Fabrique Nationale designed Mauser model 1924 short rifle. After World War II, the Yugoslavs took this design and incorporated modifications based upon Germany's MauserKarabiner 98k. Although similar in general appearance to that of the German rifle, many of the parts of these two rifles are not interchangeable, especially the bolt and related action parts. The main difference between the M48 and the K98k is that the M48 uses an intermediate-length receiver. They are usually easily identified by the top handguard, which extends behind the rear sight and ends just in front of the receiver ring, although this feature exists on other models as well.

title: For Sale:  Finnish M39 Nagant Sniper Rifle - Superb Condition
postcontent:
I purchased this rifle in 1990, admired it for a while, then greased it up and put it in my safe where it has been ever since. 

I believe it is one of a relatively small group of rifles that were assembled by the Finnish government in the 1970's for export using mothballed M39's and original PU scopes that were either captured or purchased and stockpiled by the Finn's after WWII. 

The pristine condition of the rifle along with the high quality work evident in the scope mounting seem to confirm this. I've seen many examples of the work that the big importers have done here in the states and it varies from ok/fair to downright shoddy. So again this does seem to indicate that this is one of be rifles put together in Finland then exported to the US in the 1970's.

I've done some research on this rifle and there really isn't much info available. However I did find record of some old print ads from the 70's that advertised what appears to be a very similar rifle. It went for $200 in the mid-70's which was a considerable amount at the time. 

The rifle is immaculate with metal finish near 100% with wood the same way. Bore is pristine, and the PU scope's optics are bright and clear. 

Rifle comes with an original Finn M39 green leather sling and blackened brass muzzle cap. The scope is an original PU that includes leather lens caps, heavy canvas scope/action cover, and the original lens cleaning cloth.  

Additionally there is (5) 20 round boxes of Russian 7.62 x 54 Match ammo that was made in 1971. Ammo is brass case and uses match grade powder & primers along with a 182 grain boat tail match bullet. There is also a high quality reproduction bayonet and green leather scabbard that was purchased later. Most of the original M39 bayonets were destroyed and a surviving original can cost upwards to $500 by itself. 

Finally there is some paperwork that came with the rifle. It's written in either Finnish or Russian and since I can't read either - I'm not sure. The only thing I can read is the date which is stamped in blue ink and it reads 1976. This is obviously some sort of
inspector's sign off sheet. It could be for the rifle, it could be the scope or could be both. 

I'm asking $1150 for the rifle, ammo & accessories. Pick up in the Brandon area. Must be a Florida resident and of legal age to purchase. 

Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  Lee Collet Neck Sizing Die .223/5.56x45
postcontent:
I never used this die.  Saves from overworking brass by only resizing the neck of the brass.  Ideal to resize brass that has already been fired from YOUR gun.  

When a rifle round is fired from a gun the brass expands (perfectly) to the chamber of that gun.  That's where Lee's Collet Neck Sizing Die comes in.  It only resizes the neck/mouth of the brass, keeping the shoulder perfected mated to your rifle's chamber, thus increasing accuracy!
